##"Not Dialysis is waiting to die" , the plight of the city of uremia patients

Micro-signal. NBWEEKLY

Introduction of function, new media with temperature

Every life-sustaining journey is full of uncertainty.

Feng Jie, Gao Yijia, Xie Chan, editor | Roo

Yuan has been standing at Hanyang General Hospital for over eight hours. In addition to him, on the night of January 28, nearly 20 uremic patients gathered at Hanyang General Hospital wearing nothing more than face masks.

Kidney Physicians, Hospital Security Department leaders back and forth, the two sides deadlocked, constantly waiting, discussing and even arguing. During the patients "made three 110 calls, Countless Times Health Commission calls and the Mayor Hotline, to three groups of police, " and finally wait until the hospital leadership.

Until 9:00 pm, the hospital finally promised, will not find a new dialysis venue for patients to arrange for dialysis Puai hospital, patients can first go home and other specific hospital allocation and dialysis schedule.

The number of people infected with COVID-19 pneumonia continues to rise, and clustering in hospitals is an extremely high risk behavior. But regular dialysis is the only option for these uremic patients to survive.

"without dialysis, you're just waiting to die. "

After the blood is drawn out, the artificial kidney and the hemodialysis machine will remove the excess water and toxin from the body, and then inject it back into the body through another needle tube. The dialysis, for uremic patients, takes four to six hours three times a week.

On January 26, Yuan was told among dialysis patients that the Hanyang Hospital of traditional Chinese medicine had been requisitioned as the third set of designated treatment hospitals, requiring patients to be evacuated and dialysis rooms to be closed. The nurses in charge of the docking said dialysis rooms at several hospitals that had not been requisitioned were already full, and patients who needed dialysis had to "find their own way. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The inmates are starting to panic.

The next day, the Hanyang Hospital of Traditional Chinese medicine arranged for a group of patients to be sent to private hospitals for dialysis at their own expense, while others were sent to the Hubei Provincial Hospital of traditional Chinese medicine.

Yuan Yuan was assigned to the Tianze Dialysis Center in Hanyang, afraid of not being able to dialysis after, Yuan Yuan once paid six times dialysis money, more than 2,740 yuan, not including drug costs. "The average cost of dialysis is only over 100 after serious medical insurance reimbursement. " For some dialysis patients who do not have jobs and income, the cost of nearly 3,000 yuan for two weeks is a large sum.

Several other patients at the same hospital, including Li Ping, are still searching for a new one.

"Can you contact a dialysis hospital? We can't wait for this disease, " Yuan added. "They haven't had dialysis for several days. They can't eat or drink today. "

On Jan. 29, Li Ping had been on dialysis for five days, unable to drain the fluid and suffering from Severe Edema. "Toxins can accumulate in the body if the body is not cleansed, damaging all the internal organs and other sequelae. " Over time, Arrhythmia, blood pressure will continue to rise, and may even lead to death.

Li Ping asked around and kept going to different hospitals. The road sprain foot, ankle swelling around, fortunately, the community sent a car to pick up. Because Li Ping has hep a, the blood is infectious and requires dialysis on a positive machine, and most of the hospitals she contacts are saturated and do not have machines or accept new patients.

Dialysis rooms in every hospital could face closure. Wuhan has requisitioned three batches of 24 designated hospitals and cleared nearly 10,000 beds for fever patients. A patient friend told reporters that his hospital "transferred some dialysis patients to come, the results soon became fixed point" , "dialysis once do not know there is no next time.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Some of the patients were reassigned to puren branch for dialysis

The reporter contacted the Xinzhou District Health Bureau of Wuhan City, "Many people called me today to say they want dialysis. There is no way. The hospital is full. No matter in Wuhan or Xinzhou, we can't take any more. All the hospitals are full. There is no way. "

The larger General Hospital still has the capacity to divert patients to other hospital districts. The head of the Wuhan Union Hospital confirmed to reporters that after the West Hospital of Concord was requisitioned, all patients unrelated to the outbreak have been properly triaged.

But for many more hospitals, once they've been requisitioned, dialysis rooms are closed the next day. With limited machines, some hospitals have even started night dialysis, or have reduced the number of dialysis sessions to accommodate more patients.

In the WECHAT group called "Wuhan War Epidemic" , there is still a steady stream of new uremic patients to join, gradually expanding to Hubei Province, the group constantly updated on dialysis information. Id for the "hands together, " the patient replied: "Brothers and sisters, take care of each other, if it is not possible to reduce the time to try to keep everyone alive

This sentence was immediately in the group of "Total Lu tomorrow to close the dialysis room, " the information brush off.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A Journey full of unknowns

Analysis of Li xi-xin in the First People's Hospital of Xiaogan city. 5:30 a.m. , 7:20 to the hospital, 25 miles, nearly two hours on a motorcycle. Father did not trust to go with him. When leaving the village, the intersection let the tree and cement block, waste cement pole block, clear more than 10 minutes, two people push hard just barely past, to the town also afraid of block road, took the outer ring road. In winter in Wuhan, he was cold all over.

Li Xixin considered himself lucky to have made the trip, compared with his fellow patients in the group.

Public Transport in Wuhan has been suspended since the city was closed on January 23, and traffic controls have been imposed in various urban areas of Hubei Province.

Tian Lei finished his dialysis just in time for Wuhan to close down, public transportation was suspended, and it took him five hours to get home by riding a shared bike and walking across the Qingchuan Bridge and Yangtze River Bridges. "In times of crisis, there is a great deal of perseverance, " he wrote in a friend's circle. "I can walk and bike for almost five hours when I feel Gasp, especially after dialysis, when I should be at my weakest. Came home all sweaty."

Travel is a huge burden for uremic patients, many of whom already have symptoms of organ failure, and many who can not support long walks or rides. A patient friend usually takes a bus of 15 yuan to go dialytic, took a taxi to spend 480 yuan one way now.

The community is now able to provide the necessary car service under government arrangements. Tian said many patients now go to dialysis in a car sent by the community. But different communities have different situations, some communities can not provide a car service: "for example, it's too far, it's not going anywhere. For example, the Second Hospital in Nanjing Road can provide 24-hour dialysis, but there is no car to take you at night. Different districts have different conditions, different resources and different attitudes. "

Ah Liu in the community to father about the car was temporarily canceled, this time ah Liu really anxious.

On the first day of the Lunar New Year, the 57-year-old father finished dialysis and decided to walk back without getting a taxi, but the old man walked on the wrong road. Unable to wait for his father, Liu and the police searched for hours in the rain to find the old man, never again dare to let the old man go to dialysis alone. Looking for a car everywhere Liu finally into a fleet, after several inquiries finally found the car.

Following an incident in which a driver was quarantined after being taken to hospital by a patient with fever, most of the volunteer and community convoys were reluctant to transport passengers to hospital, because "life is not guaranteed. ". In this case, the dialysis patient's travel is more difficult.

Tian also worries about elderly uremic patients who need a wheelchair to help them walk. They often have little social contact and do not join a well-informed group of patients, which can be more dangerous if they live alone.

In order to implement the "non-proliferation inside, anti-export outside" requirements, Hubei regions to more stringent measures to restrict the movement of vehicles and personnel. At about 11 am on 29 January, all street lights in Dangyang, Yichang, turned red and all vehicles were banned. Xiaogan has banned electric vehicles as well as motor vehicles since midnight on January 30,2020.

Villages and towns have set up a large number of physical barriers, thatch, horizontal trucks, stone piers have been used as roadblocks, between the village, town, city for the identity of the pass, was often stopped to negotiate for several hours.

Every life-sustaining trip for a dialysis patient is fraught with uncertainty.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A road block photographed by a uremic patient.

Bird on a Wire

Before dialysis, Li Xinxi did as much protection as possible at home. He puts on a long down jacket with a Hoodie, wears a surgical mask and a cotton mask, puts the hat on and ties it tight to reveal only two eyes. He feels that everyone "is a Bird on a Wire, and everyone is a germ except himself. ".

Soldier never got a new mask, and every time he was in and out of the hospital, he would go home and boil it at high temperature, dry it, and spray it with the remaining bit of alcohol.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The soldier's repeated use of masks.

Under the epidemic situation, Wuhan Tianlin chinese-western Combined Hospital (later referred to as "chinese-western hospital") has become a special dialysis room.

Chinese and Western hospital is a private kidney hospital, admission of nearly 60 people need dialysis in uremia patients. The hospital is only two stops away from the south China Seafood Market. As they are private hospitals and do not receive pneumonia patients, the Chinese and Western hospitals are unable to obtain protective clothing and disinfection supplies provided by the Health Commission.

On January 26th, after hospital officials decided to close down, fellow patients who had nowhere to put them on dialysis contacted doctors and nurses to discuss doing it in private. But the shortage of protective materials has always been a problem. The Masks and protective clothing in the hospital have all been used up. At first, patients collected more than a dozen protective clothing through volunteers, and arranged for patients with private cars to pick up and drop off four nurses, it lasted three days and provided dialysis treatment to nearly 60 patients. But when the suits ran out, the nurses were afraid to go on dialysis.

The Sixth Hospital of Wuhan City, although designated hospital, but in uremia patients under the strong demand, still at the same time to treat fever patients and open dialysis room. But this brings new risks. Uremia patients with poor immunity, the risk of infection is higher than the general population.

On the one hand, hospitals that admit patients with fever are afraid of cross-infection and the spread of the epidemic and dare not admit other common patients; on the other hand, because of the presence of asymptomatic carriers, non-designated hospitals can not exclude asymptomatic carriers only by taking body temperature, afraid to take on new patients.

Wuhan, January 28, "on the new epidemic of pneumonia during the health care work of special people, " said in the notice, "ensure the demand for health care services for people with confirmed and suspected cases of COVID-19 pneumonia with chronic kidney failure, maternal and surgical diseases. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Since Wuhan is at the height of the epidemic, hospital departments are often afraid to admit new patients to prevent cross-infection when only one case of COVID-19 pneumonia is detected.

But for other patients who are not infected but are at high risk of infection, all medical resources are skewed in favor of those with fevers, who need protection and hope for survival.

Uremic patients are not alone. On January 29, a family member of a acute leukemia patient asked for help on Weibo. Because there was no hospital to receive it, and because the city was closed, there was no blood donation and the blood bank was in dire need. The patient could not be admitted to the hospital or even eligible to queue for a blood transfusion. And can not timely transfusion of platelets, there will be internal bleeding at any time the risk of death.

In Wuhan, the government takes over the needs of hospitals, and community liaison officers are responsible for registering information through the "Wuhan Micro-neighborhood" small program. But for non-pneumonia patients, how to ensure the medical needs of other patients is still a problem that needs to be solved.

Among the group of patients, they encouraged each other: "dialysis has lasted more than a decade, and the method is always more difficult than the method. " But for the Wuhan Xinzhou District Health Bureau, who has been answering the phone nonstop, he could only repeat it over and over again, "We don't have a solution. It's really special. We don't have a solution without dialysis. We don't have a solution. "
